    "lesson4-content": {
        "title": "Lesson 4 - Sorry and Excuse me",
        "contents": [
                       {
                       "title": "죄송합니다.",
                       "content":"죄송 [joe-song] means 'apology', 'being sorry' or 'feeling ashamed', and 합니다 [hap-ni- da] means 'I do', so 죄송합니다 [joe-song-hap-ni-da] means 'I am sorry.' or 'I apologize.'"
                       },
                       { 
                        "title": "죄송합니다 is NOT always 'I’m sorry'.",
                       "content":"Even though 죄송합니다 [joe-song-hap-ni-da] is BASICALLY 'I’m sorry', you can’t use 죄송합니 다 when you want to say 'I am sorry to hear that.' This is because 죄송합니다 ONLY means 'I apologize.', 'It was my bad.', 'Excuse me.' or 'I shouldn’t have done that.' It can never mean 'I’m sorry to hear that.'"
                       },
                       {
                       "title": "저기요.",
                       "content": "저기요 [jeo-gi-yo] is an expression that can be translated to 'Excuse me' but this Korean expression, 저기요 is ONLY used when you want to get someone’s attention and talk to them or let them know something or when you want to call the waiter in a restaurant or a cafe to order something."
                       },
                       {
                       "title": "How do you say “Excuse me.” when you want to pass through?",
                       "content": "You can say: 잠시만요 (just a second) or 잠깐만요 (just a second), or 죄송합니다 (I'm sorry)."
                       }
                       ],
